The paper discusses the use of Generative Adversarial Networks (GANs) for language generation and proposes alternative metrics for evaluating the quality and diversity of generated samples. This topic falls under the sub-category of Natural Language Processing (NLP) and Machine Learning (ML), which are covered by cs.CL and cs.LG respectively. The paper also discusses the sensitivity of GAN models to hyperparameters and initialization, which is a common issue in ML and could be classified under cs.AI. Additionally, the paper mentions the use of GANs for image generation, which could be classified under cs.CV. Finally, the paper conducts experiments comparing GAN models to a conventional Language Model (LM), which could be classified under cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing).
